And that's all I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who are dealing every day with a torrent of sexist or racist reactions, but do not allow themselves to be intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that bad scams are apparently considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn argued last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church and with every ‘motion of distrust’ or change of selection rules the party becomes less mindful.
Over the past two years, I’ve often been advised to keep me cheerful, not just to proclaim my opinion loudly, and then I wouldn’t ‘get into trouble’.
But I didn't go into politics before that.
Since joining Labour as a schoolchild 32 years ago, provoked by the neglect of Thatcher’s government that literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated for better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a councillor and in my role as a minister.
I have never kept my politics hidden, not even in the last election.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy positions and my disagreements with the current leadership.
To those who have promoted the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country drags on to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in fact I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a member of parliament for the next election or your political opportunities will not stop me from trading.
