'The sea is ours': the landlocked Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the path to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors patrol in a hull-clad naval office in La Paz.
At public buildings waving an ocean blue flag.
On all naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: “The sea is ours.
It’s a duty to win them back.”
Across Bolivia’s countryside, the memory of the coastline that the country had to give up to Chile after a bloody nineteenth-century resource conflict is still alive, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
That hope may have reached its highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice, which should fall on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course looks forward to the result with positive prospects,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will look at the court’s ruling on the big screen, hoping that the court in The Hague will plead in favor of Bolivia that Chile, after decades of spicy talks, is obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Also for Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is facing a controversial fight for re-election next year, much is at stake with Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he swore at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia, and even if it did, little would change.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands does not have the authority to allocate Chilean territory and has indicated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
That the International Court of Justice’s ruling comes just six months after the closing arguments indicates that the case was “not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And the prospects for a positive outcome of Bolivia have certainly not improved, on the contrary, the situation has perhaps even worsened in the last four years.
“The case of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian government,” Zárate said.
Morales’ warlike rhetoric has all the goodwill that Chile might have completely undermined, she said.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to talk further afterwards.
The two countries have not had an ambassador in each other’s country since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, denies that the court’s decision was taken unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will have “an extraordinary opportunity to begin a new era of international relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “end 139 years of differences, with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, uses the maritime issue as a political stool.
