John Edward: Language Skills Essential for World Citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent state of service in the field of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other initiatives from across the community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for continuing and higher education, the careers they choose and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects by excellence within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can not only rely on English when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can deduce that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest passing rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the German students, 69 percent of the French students and 63 percent of the Spanish students also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as subject matter as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of the obstacles to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language knowledge, according to employers.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for their future careers.
As more and more vacancies require language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, in the future he will have a real advantage with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation. French was the only language that stood out above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for children today.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest is, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
There is currently no denying that languages in a global business environment remain vital to the country's future, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
