North Korea says it will “in no case” unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions are leading to increasing mistrust in the United States and that under such circumstances the country could in no way give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho told the U.N.’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site for nuclear tests and promising not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We do not see a corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves."
Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it took further steps, it was noted that he did not a priori reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang did earlier.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the very first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised guarantees for the security of North Korea.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States is urging 'denuclearization first' and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the 'declaration of the end of war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an air castle of the people who are unaware of us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only strengthen our mistrust.”
Ri did not report plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the U.S. leader said earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party on this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be such a step.
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different than last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles would be aimed at the U.S. mainland so after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, praised Kim this year at the United Nations for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said there is still much to do and that sanctions must remain until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday, “The enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must be vigorously and decisively continued until we have achieved the full, final, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to significantly reduce funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo had a meeting with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making "gangster-like demands."
North Korea promised this month during a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States took "appropriate measures".
He said Kim had told him that the "appropriate measures" he wanted were security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take Course on the Importance of Sufficient Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will ensure that all students get more sleep, in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night while drinking plenty of caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world’s largest university often have no idea the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist associated with Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course, which, as far as he knows, is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I hearing this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which will be organized for the first time this year, will explain to students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was found that students had a severe sleep deficiency during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise devices and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine when going to sleep.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we find that they have the right to know all this, just as people have the right to know what consequences the choice for cigarettes has on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of one-night stand pride still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deficiency causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course, because he had taken classes with the professor last year when he studied at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, not just an alarm to wake up. They also need to be aware of the damaging effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronics screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, causing you to struggle to fall asleep.
