The Global Citizen Festival, which was first organized in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a group of international advocates who hope to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting against it.
Concert attendees who wanted to get a free ticket for the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket) had to complete a series of tasks, or "actions", such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or otherwise generating meaningful awareness for the purpose.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, with another 12 years to go to achieve this goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert an appropriate way to convince people to demand a call to action or is this just another form of “clitivism,” making people feel like they are making a real contribution by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen, more than 19 million “actions” of supporters have been registered, targeting a large number of different goals.
According to Global Citizen, these actions have contributed to global leaders’ commitment and policy proposals worth more than $37 billion that need to change the lives of 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 initiatives and statements based on the actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid out or collected through sponsorship actions.
The group estimates that the funds obtained so far have had an impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Among the main statements of intent is that of The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and executives from the UK with the aim of “helping children realize their full potential”. This group has pledged $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the help of the UK government, donors, other national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make a footnote in history of the social injustice that is malnutrition,” said Tracey Ullman, ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, to the public at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also announced that, after more than 5,000 actions were sent out asking the UK government to improve the nutritional situation for mothers and children, the government has announced a project, the Power of Nutrition, to support 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the most frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen website, “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”
The group replied: "It will be a long and difficult journey, in which we will sometimes fall and fail.
But, just like the civil rights and anti-apartheid movements ahead of us, we will ultimately be successful because together we are stronger.
