The inventor of the World Wide Web plans a new Internet to address Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, starts a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of the technology legend, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
Solid gives users the ability to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that ‘world domination’ is the leading thought behind Inrupt.
“We have to do this now,” he said of the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to enable people to create their own “personal online data storage” or POD.
It can store contact lists, activity lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together via one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is the fact that it depends entirely on the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company provides the resources, processes, and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team will not hold talks with "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete transformation that will completely overturn all of their business models at once."
"We don't ask for their permission."
In a post on Medium published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that the “mission (of Inrupt) is to deliver the commercial energy and ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web, which is built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this new era for the web,” Berners-Lee added.
