The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats.
New research conducted on a estate in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown big eagle bat, and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's screams and what kind of what does.
A map of the habitat and a report are then produced to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS conservation advisor, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making pastures and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Flea populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, just like flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Butterflies are not actually blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly investigate, inspect sleeping places and sometimes carry out rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten species of bats live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much about bats is not yet known and therefore the work we are doing here and in other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of controlling bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could result in the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially exterminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland’s official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and many of our species simply don’t know how their populations are going.”
